{{Infobox song <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Songs --> | Name = 25 Minutes to Go | Type = | Artist = [[Shel Silverstein]] | Album = Inside Folk Songs | A-side = | Recorded = | Released = {{Start date|1962}} | Published = | Genre = [[Country music|Country]] | Language = | Length = <!-- {{Duration|m=MM|s=SS}} --> | Writer = [[Shel Silverstein]] | Composer = | Label = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] | Producer = | Tracks = | prev = "Boa Constrictor" | prev_no = 7 | track_no = 8 | next = "Folk Singer's Blues" | next_no = 9 }} "'''25 Minutes to Go'''" is a song by [[Shel Silverstein]], from his 1962 album ''Inside Folk Songs''.<ref name="allmusic-album">{{cite web|title=Inside Folk Songs - Shel Silverstein {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/inside-folk-songs-mw0000494004|website=AllMusic|accessdate=10 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130025053/http://www.allmusic.com/album/inside-folk-songs-mw0000494004|archivedate=30 November 2015}}</ref>
==Lyrics== The song is literally "[[gallows humor]]", as it is sung by a man awaiting his own execution by hanging. Each verse consists of two lines, of which the first line is anything from humorous to poignant, and the second line is a minute-by-minute countdown.
:Well they're buildin' the gallows outside my cell. :I got 25 minutes to go.
:And in 25 minutes I'll be in hell. :I got 24 minutes to go.
The song is similar in concept to Silverstein's children's song "Boa Constrictor": It presents the point of view of someone who is experiencing a calamity in "real time," composing and singing as the events unfold, with a fatal conclusion. "Boa Constrictor", like "25 Minutes to Go", appeared on Silverstein's 1962 album ''Inside Folk Songs''.<ref name="allmusic-album" />
