{{Infobox journal | title = Wíčazo Ša Review | cover = Wicazo.jpg | editor = [[James Riding In]] | discipline = [[Native American studies]] | abbreviation = Wicazo Sa Rev. | publisher = [[University of Minnesota Press]] | country = United States | frequency = Biannually | history = 1985-present | openaccess = | license = | impact = | impact-year = | website = http://www.upress.umn.edu/journal-division/Journals/wicazo-sa-review | link1 = http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/wic/Journal | link1-name = Online access at [[Project MUSE]] | link2 = | link2-name = | JSTOR = 07496427 | OCLC = 730022200 | LCCN = 90656087 | CODEN = | ISSN = 0749-6427 | eISSN = 1533-7901 }} The '''''Wíčazo Ša Review''''' ("Red Pencil" in [[Lakota language|Lakota]]) is a biannual [[peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] of [[Native American studies]]. The journal was established in 1985 by [[editors-in-chief]] [[Elizabeth Cook-Lynn]], [[Roger Buffalohead]], and [[William Willard (anthropologist)|William Willard]]. ''Wíčazo Ša Review'' is published by the [[University of Minnesota Press]], which acquired it in 1999. Originally it was published at [[Eastern Washington University]], under the guidance of its Native American Studies center. Issues include essays, articles, interviews, reviews, poems, short stories, course outlines, curriculum designs, scholarly research and literary criticism reflective of Native American studies and related fields. The current editor is [[James Riding In]] ([[Arizona State University]]).
